Satellite day @FBN: ggplot2-Plotting Anything

Author

Anja Eggert

Published

March 5, 2025

R Libraries

Please note that the package ggplot2 is included in the tidy universe:

library(tidyverse)     # tidy universe
library(viridis)       # colour scales
library(patchwork)     # combine plots

library(agridat)       # agricultural data sets

Data sets

You can use data from the agridat R package or your own data. But also other packages come with data sets. You can see the list of pre-loaded data, type the function data():

data()
?agridat # list all datasets with keywords
starte den http Server fÃ¼r die Hilfe fertig

Choose and load one data set of your choice using data("name_of_dataset"). The you see means that the object hasnât been fully evaluated yet. This happens because the data is lazily loaded from the package but hasnât been accessed yet.

data("crampton.pig")

head(crampton.pig)

3        T1  R3      21  661     180

You could also type this:

dat <- agridat::crampton.pig

Some data wrangling

I like to use the tidy way of data processing. Therefore I suggest to convert the data table into a tibble. We also convert columns into factors.

dat <- as_tibble(dat) |> 
  mutate_at(vars(treatment, 
                 rep), ~as.factor(.))

dat

Building simple ggplots

Empty plot

This only creates an empty plot, without any layers.

ggplot(data = dat,
       aes(x = feed, y = weight2))

You can run the code without typing âdata =â. It is just shorter.

ggplot(dat,
       aes(x = feed, y = weight2))

Or you can also pipe the data into ggplot:

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2))

Simple scatter plot

Now we add geom_point() to create a scatter plot. The components of a ggplot are combined with +.

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2)) +
  geom_point()

geom_point() is a shortcut. Behind the scenes it calls the layer() function to create a new layer:

layer(
  mapping = NULL, 
  data = NULL,
  geom = "point", geom_params = list(),
  stat = "identity", stat_params = list(),
  position = "identity"
)

Add more layers

Combine a scatter and a line plot and choose a theme of your choice. Please recognize that the order of the layers matters:

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2)) +
  geom_line(colour = "tomato", linewidth = 1, linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_point(size = 3, colour = "grey60", shape = 15) +
  theme_bw()

Do you see the difference?

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, colour = "grey60", shape = 15) +
  geom_line(colour = "tomato", linewidth = 1, linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_bw()

More complex ggplots

The group aesthetic

The group aesthetic controls how data points are connected or grouped for certain geometries (geom_). When you use:

ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, group = treatment))

it means that observations sharing the same value of treatment are treated as a group in the visualization. The effect of this depends on the type of geom used:

When group = treatment is specified in a line plot, it ensures that each level of treatment gets its own separate line.

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, group = treatment, col = treatment)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 0.5, linetype = "solid") +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       col = "Treatment") +
  theme_bw()

Statistical transformations

Add a statistics layer, here lm function to smooth the data.

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, colour = "grey60") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_bw()

For scatter plots, group usually is not needed because each point is independent. But if used in combination with geom_smooth(), it affects how trend lines are drawn.

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, group = treatment)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       col = "Treatment") +
  theme_bw()
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Jittering

Jittering is useful when data points overlap too much, making it hard to see individual observations. Instead of plotting points exactly at their values, jittering adds a small random variation, helping to reduce overplotting and make patterns more visible.

dat |>  
  dplyr::filter(treatment %in% c("T1", "T2")) |> 
  mutate(jit = jitter(as.numeric(treatment), 0.3)) |>  
  ggplot(aes(y = weight2)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = treatment),
               col = "black", fill = NA, 
               outlier.shape = NA, width=0.5,
               position = position_dodge(0.5)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = jit, group = rep), 
            col = "grey80", linewidth = 0.2) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = jit), size = 2) +
  theme_minimal()

Scales

Scales control how data is mapped to aesthetics (e.g., x, y, color, size). Each type of data: continuous, discrete, and date/time, requires the right scale function to properly represent it.

Continuous scales

Use a colour scale from the viridis package:

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, col = weight1)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(500, 900), 
                     breaks = seq(500,900,50)) +
  scale_colour_viridis(discrete = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       col = "Initial weight (kg)") +
  theme_classic()

Discrete scales

Use a colour scale from the viridis package:

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = treatment, y = weight2, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("A", "B", "C", "D", "E")) +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE) +
  labs(x = "Treatment",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)") +
  theme_classic()

You can define your manual scale:

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = treatment, y = weight2, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("A", "B", "C", "D", "E")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", 
                               "blue", 
                               "green", 
                               "orange",
                               "yellow")) +
  labs(x = "Treatment",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)") +
  theme_classic()

Dates and times

This is a data set of daily air quality measurements in New York, May to September 1973.

air <- data("airquality")

air <- as_tibble(airquality) |> 
   mutate(
    Month = str_pad(Month, width = 2, side = "left", pad = "0"),
    Day = str_pad(Day, width = 2, side = "left", pad = "0"),
    Date = ymd(paste(1973, Month, Day, sep = "-"))
  )

We plot the data and add a box and some text.

In the theme, the size is defined in pts. So here 15, means 15 pts. In geom_text, the size is defined in mm, so itâs 15 mm. What is the relation between pts and mm or in? If we want exactly the same size for the title and the text in the plot, we can apply this conversion:

# from pt to mm : mm = pt / .pt -> 15 / 2.845276 = 5.27
ggplot2::.pt
[1] 2.845276

If the date labels are shown in German, we can change this. Set Locale to English Use the Sys.setlocale() function to set the locale for the language you want.

# Sys.setlocale("LC_TIME", "English_United States.UTF-8")
rect <- data.frame(xmin=as.Date(-Inf), xmax=as.Date(Inf), ymin=25, ymax=30)

air |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y= (Temp - 32)/(9/5))) +
  geom_rect(data=rect,
            aes(xmin=xmin, xmax=xmax, ymin=ymin, ymax=ymax),
            fill="yellow", alpha=0.3, inherit.aes = FALSE) +
  geom_line(colour="grey30") +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "1 month",
               date_labels = "%b",
               limits=c(as.Date("1973-05-01"), as.Date("1973-09-30"))) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(10,40),
                     breaks=seq(10, 40, by = 5)) +
  labs(x = "1973",
       y = "Temperature (Â°C)") +
  annotate("text", x = as.Date('1973-05-15'), y = 40,
           label = "New York",
           size = 4, hjust = 0, colour = "grey20") +
  theme_bw()

Facet Mapping

Variables of the data set are used to define the sub-plots, i.e.Â many plots with the same type of plot. Very useful to get a quick overview of larger data sets.

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)") +
  facet_wrap(~treatment) +
  theme_bw()

Legends

Boxplots

The default legend of a boxplot is ugly. The shapes are not reactangles, but tiny boxplots. This is an easy way to prevent this:

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = treatment, y = weight2, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("A", "B", "C", "D", "E")) +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE) +
  labs(x = "Treatment",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       fill = "Treatment") +
  my_theme +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(override.aes = list(linetype = 0, size  = 5)))
Error: Objekt 'my_theme' nicht gefunden

Single legend

In this case we want to colour the points and also use different shapes. Without the trick, two legends would be shown. Matching title ensures a single legend.

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, col = treatment, shape = treatment)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(500, 900), 
                     breaks = seq(500,900,50)) +
  scale_colour_viridis(discrete = TRUE) +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       col = "Initial weight (kg)",
       shape = "Initial weight (kg)") +
  theme_classic()

Define custom theme

Creating a custom ggplot2 theme allows you to control the overall appearance of your plots, ensuring consistency across multiple visualizations. When defining your own theme, you can adjust several components to tailor the plotâs style.

my_theme = theme_classic() +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "sans"),
        plot.title   = element_text(face = "plain", size = 16),
        axis.title   = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16),
        axis.text    = element_text(size = 14, angle = 0, vjust = 0.5),
        legend.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16),
        legend.text  = element_text(face = "plain", size = 16),
        strip.text   = element_text(size = 16),
        legend.position = "top",
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

Now we apply this own theme to a plot:

dat |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = treatment, y = weight2, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("A", "B", "C", "D", "E")) +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE) +
  labs(x = "Treatment",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)") +
  my_theme

Combining plots with patchwork

The patchwork package is a powerful and flexible tool for combining multiple ggplots into a single layout. It is simple to use and provides a variety of options to control the arrangement of plots.

p1 <- dat |> 
  dplyr::filter(treatment == "T1") |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, col = weight1)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(500, 900), 
                     breaks = seq(500,900,50)) +
  scale_colour_viridis(discrete = FALSE, guide = "none") +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       col = "Initial weight (kg)") +
  theme_classic()

p2 <- dat |> 
  dplyr::filter(treatment == "T2") |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, col = weight1)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(500, 900), 
                     breaks = seq(500,900,50)) +
  scale_colour_viridis(discrete = FALSE, guide = "none") +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       col = "Initial weight (kg)") +
  theme_classic()

p3 <- dat |> 
  dplyr::filter(treatment == "T3") |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, col = weight1)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(500, 900), 
                     breaks = seq(500,900,50)) +
  scale_colour_viridis(discrete = FALSE, guide = "none") +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       col = "Initial weight (kg)") +
  theme_classic()

p4 <- dat |> 
  dplyr::filter(treatment == "T4") |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = feed, y = weight2, col = weight1)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(500, 900), 
                     breaks = seq(500,900,50)) +
  scale_colour_viridis(discrete = FALSE, guide = "none") +
  labs(x = "Feed",
       y = "Final body mass (kg)",
       col = "Initial weight (kg)") +
  theme_classic()
combined <- p1 + p2 + p3 + p4 + 
  plot_layout(ncol = 2, guides = "collect") +
  scale_colour_viridis(discrete = FALSE) +
  plot_annotation(tag_levels = 'A') &
  theme(plot.tag = element_text(face = "bold", size = 20),
        legend.position = "bottom",
        legend.direction = "horizontal")
